## Methodology
Not found

## Results
results are confounded by the 
intelligence quotient (IQ). Associations 
between brain volume and IQ have 
been shown across studies of adults 
and children.3 Patients with ADHD and 
other psychiatric conditions appear to 
have lower intelligence than those in 
the general population4 and their non-
afflicted siblings.5
We have reanalysed the data for 
Cohen’s d reported by Hoogman and 
colleagues in relation to IQ (table). To 
do our analysis, we re-estimated the 
effect sizes by means of mixed-effects 
meta-regression because we did not 
have access to the individual level data 
of the mega-analysis. Consequently, 
we examined the effect of adding the 
IQ difference between groups as a 
meta-regression variable.
We found that adjustment for IQ 
reduced the association between 
brain volume and ADHD in most 
but not all areas of the brain, and 
increased the range of the 95% CIs 
considerably. Differences between 
reported and re-estimated values are 
possibly due primarily to the fact that 
the original analysis was done with 
individual participant data, whereas 
the reanalysis was an ordinary group 
level meta-analysis. Data and analysis 
code are available online.
