The neuroimaging study by Martine 
Hoogman and colleagues1 showed 
more extensive differences in the 
brains of people with attention deficit 
hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) than 
would be anticipated from the DSM-5 
diagnostic criteria. The involvement 
of regions of the brain associated with 
emotional regulation is particularly 
interesting. According to DSM-5, 
ADHD is a condition with no intrinsic 
emotional component.
However, the findings fit with the 
close association that clinicians observe 
between ADHD and oppositional 
defiant disorder (ODD), with ODD 
diagnosable in around 40% of children 
with ADHD.2 Given that symptom 
severity could be considered a 
continuous variable, a proportion of 
people diagnosed with ADHD even 
higher than 40% probably have features 
of ODD but do not reach diagnostic 
thresholds. ODD symptoms including 
moodiness, negativity, and aggression 
often contribute substantially to the 
overall level of disability in ADHD.
Hoogman and colleagues’ study 
called for more sophisticated models 
of ADHD than existing models. One 
such model is the dual pathway 
model proposed by Sonuga-Barke and 
colleagues,3 which is framed in terms of 
impairments that can be identified by 
neuropsychological testing. However, 
